@flexiarg relationship-coherence/co-created-project
@title Enrol the Idea as a Joint Artifact
@sigils [📓/共]
@keywords co-creation, shared-project, commonplace-book, collaboration, artifact, ledger, joint-work
@audience correspondents who build things to hold a bond
@references [relationship-coherence/resonance-weaving relationship-coherence/lexicon-minting]
@references-extra ["Instance of origin: 2026-04-26 — Julia, 'Our little book is going to fill up fast... I surpassed our one-page limit.' Recurs as a standing habit of naming joint artifacts: the commonplace book, an emoji cookbook, a 'connective words' guide, the Repertoire Remix, music duets, a shared summer reading list."]
@tone declarative
@style pattern

! conclusion: When an idea or interest surfaces, enrol it as a *named joint artifact* to build together — a commonplace book, a cookbook, a remix, a reading list — so the bond has a growing object it is making.

  + context: Beyond weaving references into talk, this pair keeps starting shared things to make. The artifacts accumulate as a parallel record of the relationship's productivity.

  + IF:
    a shared enthusiasm appears that could be left as conversation or turned into a thing you build together.

  + HOWEVER:
    a project only bonds if it is actually named and added to (an aspirational 'we should make X' that never gets an entry is not a shared artifact); and too many open projects dilute rather than deepen.

  + THEN:
    give it a name and a first entry, and treat it as jointly owned and added-to over time.

  + BECAUSE:
    a co-created object externalises the relationship into something that grows and can be pointed at; making-together is a mode of being-together that outlasts any single exchange.

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    - Distinguish from relationship-coherence/resonance-weaving: weaving links references into a shared *web*; this pattern builds a shared *object*.
    - The couple's private lexicon (relationship-coherence/lexicon-minting) is itself one such artifact.
